WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.530 --> 00:00:03.940
Finding long lost relatives can be really tricky, especially if you don't

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:06.760
have a good place to start, but it's a lot easier if you

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:10.540
have the help from someone like a Genetic Genealogist, and today we lucky

00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:16.030
enough to be joined remotely with CC Moore, a Genetic Genealogist. Hi CC.

00:00:16.030 --> 00:00:16.968
&gt;&gt; Hi Matt, how are you?

00:00:16.968 --> 00:00:20.812
&gt;&gt; I'm doing pretty good, you know we pretty excited to be learning all

00:00:20.812 --> 00:00:23.230
about this Ancestry and Human Evolution, and

00:00:23.230 --> 00:00:25.810
we're really curious at this point. You know,

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:28.022
what is it that a genetic genealogist does?

00:00:28.022 --> 00:00:30.682
&gt;&gt; A genetic genealogist uses DNA testing in

00:00:30.682 --> 00:00:34.634
conjunction with traditional genealogy research in order to

00:00:34.634 --> 00:00:39.503
learn more about our roots. And so, does this mean that you have to go through

00:00:39.503 --> 00:00:41.766
a service like 23 and me, a similar

00:00:41.766 --> 00:00:44.978
service like Family Tree, dna.com, what do you

00:00:44.978 --> 00:00:47.533
need as an individual who is interested in

00:00:47.533 --> 00:00:51.040
finding out more along the lines of genetic genealogy?

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:55.790
&gt;&gt; Well you need to take a direct-to-consumer genetic genealogy test.

00:00:55.790 --> 00:00:59.700
So yes, that can be 23 and me, Ancestry DNA, or Family

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:04.910
Tree DNA. Also, also National Geographic Genome 2.0, although that's more

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:09.250
focused on ancient ancestry, then it is applicable to our family trees.

00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:12.590
&gt;&gt; I see, and how do, how do you get in touch with people? How do

00:01:12.590 --> 00:01:14.030
you interact with people, do they come to

00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:16.710
you with questions, do you help them find relatives?

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:19.152
&gt;&gt; We have a very active genetic genealogy

00:01:19.152 --> 00:01:22.466
community. We have have lots of forums and mailing

00:01:22.466 --> 00:01:25.730
lists and there's people posting questions and answers

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:28.340
all day long on these lists. So that the

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:31.640
best way to, get involved and really learn

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:34.740
how we're using DNA testing for geneaology. Also, to

00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:37.140
get answers from a lot of the experts. We

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:43.065
have really an amazing community with incredibly intelligent and

00:01:43.065 --> 00:01:47.150
knowledgeable people who are willing to help for free on these lists.

00:01:47.150 --> 00:01:51.310
So that's really how I would recommend getting started. You know, sign up,

00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:54.560
take the test with one of the companies, and while you're waiting for

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:57.430
your results, get on one of the lists and start learning right away.

00:01:57.430 --> 00:02:01.160
&gt;&gt; Now, what kind of consumers end up

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:02.950
interested in this kind of thing? Do you find

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:05.220
mainly just people with a generic interest, or

00:02:05.220 --> 00:02:08.509
do you find a lot of, maybe adopted individuals?

00:02:08.509 --> 00:02:10.940
&gt;&gt; I think all of the above. When we

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:14.290
first started with Genetic Genealogy the early adopters were

00:02:14.290 --> 00:02:17.918
highly educated. A lot of times retired scientists of

00:02:17.918 --> 00:02:21.650
not geneticists but other types of scientists, and professionals

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:26.080
from other industries, and now as we've gone further

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:28.750
with it and it's gotten more visibility, it among

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:31.330
the general populace. We have a lot more people

00:02:31.330 --> 00:02:33.680
coming in from all walks of life, all different

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:36.690
types of jobs, different ages and certainly

00:02:36.690 --> 00:02:39.810
adoptees. Because DNA testing for an adoptee

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:42.440
is just a revelation, especially for one

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:45.160
who had no knowledge of their biological roots.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.630
&gt;&gt; Now that raises an interesting question I think for

00:02:47.630 --> 00:02:51.160
me and other people is, we don't often put a

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:55.320
lot of thought into the considerations, ethical or otherwise, even

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:59.250
just emotional or psychological. What are some of the important aspects

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:00.440
that you think people should be

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:02.690
thinking about whenever they're approaching this idea

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:06.970
of finding family members, and trying to reach out and grow their family?

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:11.220
&gt;&gt; I always say expect unexpected surprises. I give a lot of

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:13.455
speeches about genetic genealogy, and I've

00:03:13.455 --> 00:03:15.980
incorporated that in every one now, and

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:21.024
lots of my writings about genetic genealogy as well. And that's because my

00:03:21.024 --> 00:03:24.920
experience has been that you just don't know what you're going to find.

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:27.770
There have been a tremendous number of people who have

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:30.950
found close family members who had no idea that that

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:34.370
other person existed. So, be prepared. And if you are

00:03:34.370 --> 00:03:38.010
not prepared to learn the truth, then you probably shouldn't test.

00:03:38.010 --> 00:03:41.210
&gt;&gt; I see. Now, that makes it sound very interesting. I

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:44.850
take it not all the responses or reactions are always positive.

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:47.825
&gt;&gt; The vast majority have been positive. But,

00:03:47.825 --> 00:03:50.170
sometimes it just takes time getting used to.

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:51.590
When you don't know that you have a half

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:55.400
sibling or a child out there sometimes. Or a

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:59.180
first cousin, nephew. Aunt, uncle, all of these types

00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:02.330
of relationships have been discovered. It's a shock, of

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:06.310
course, I've been, been a part of a lot

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:09.180
of great reunions where everyone was thrilled to meet

00:04:09.180 --> 00:04:11.850
each other. But you know, it's not an easy

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:15.190
thing to add a new family member. Especially someone

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:15.860
so close.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:18.570
&gt;&gt; Is there any particular relationship that you help

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:21.050
people find or that you just find that other

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:23.230
people end up discovering on their own that seems

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:25.810
to be more profound than other kinds of relationships?

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:29.170
&gt;&gt; I think a parent-child relationship is the most

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:33.534
profound one you can find. particularly a mother, though I

00:04:33.534 --> 00:04:37.240
think it's also true for fathers. But when mothers

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.290
have carried a child for nine months and then given

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:43.900
it up for adoption, it's an extremely emotional thing

00:04:43.900 --> 00:04:46.800
to rediscover that person. So, I think it does take

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:50.730
a lot of, adapting. Sometimes those birth mothers have been

00:04:50.730 --> 00:04:55.030
searching for their child they gave up for decades. And,

00:04:55.030 --> 00:04:57.360
or even if they weren't searching or was hoping

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:00.710
that that child would find them. And so they're thrilled

00:05:00.710 --> 00:05:03.690
but a lot of times they already have another family.

00:05:03.690 --> 00:05:05.850
So they have a husband and they have children, and

00:05:05.850 --> 00:05:07.760
they don't always know about the existence of

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.110
that other family member. So it takes a

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:14.060
little bit of time and sensitivity to integrate

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:16.890
that new family member. I, I have not

00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:21.700
actually personally seen any negative responses from birth

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:25.490
mothers or children being reunited. There have been

00:05:25.490 --> 00:05:27.370
some birth fathers who didn't know of the

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:31.040
child's existence. Who have had a harder time accepting

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:33.810
the truth of it. And if they don't understand genetics

00:05:33.810 --> 00:05:36.620
and they don't understand, you know, the test that we're using,

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:39.510
I think sometimes it's hard to convince these people that

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:42.870
yes, this is your child. And I have been a part

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:46.870
of a situation where the father denied, the birth father

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:49.120
denied at the time that he could have been the father

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:50.940
and that's partly why the child was given up for

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:56.510
adoption. And when this adoptee found a match at 23 and

00:05:56.510 --> 00:05:58.380
me which turned out to be a paternal aunt,

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:02.060
he was still unable to accept the truth of this.

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:05.150
Although the whole extended family has now accepted that

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.820
this adoptee into their family. And one of the really

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:10.682
interesting things about that case is, I used the

00:06:10.682 --> 00:06:14.620
MT DNA and the X chromosome inheritance in order to

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:18.320
narrow down exactly what the relationship was between these

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:21.730
people because they shared, I think it was 28% about,

00:06:21.730 --> 00:06:23.850
of their DNA. So as you know there could

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:27.400
be a couple of different relationships in this case.

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:30.270
And by looking at the X chromosome inheritance, we

00:06:30.270 --> 00:06:32.540
were able to narrow it down and say that this

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:35.970
is definitely a paternal aunt and she had her

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:39.260
other brother test. So also paternal uncle, we confirmed

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:42.810
it. And the father still denied it, the birth

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:46.850
father, so they hired a geneticist to look over it.

00:06:46.850 --> 00:06:49.690
And he thought that I was being too specific

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:52.480
with my claim but I think that's because he

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.620
doesn't understand how we're using DNA testing for genealogy

00:06:56.620 --> 00:07:00.040
and for these adoption searches. And so later when

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:02.640
we found the birth mother. Which we found when

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:05.870
she transferred her raw data to family tree DNA's

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:08.320
family finder. Believe it or not we found a

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:11.850
maternal first cousin. So in half an hour I

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:14.220
was able to locate the birth mother. And

00:07:14.220 --> 00:07:17.510
when she was contacted, she confirmed that the person

00:07:17.510 --> 00:07:20.600
we had identified as the birth father was indeed,

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:23.200
and they have gone to the same college, same

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:26.490
year, I mean it was very clear. So, that

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:29.750
case, has mostly turned out great, she's had a

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:33.040
wonderful reunion with her mother and with her paternal

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:36.910
extended family, but the father still has never admitted

00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:40.770
that he is indeed the father. So, it's sensitive, yeah.

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:42.300
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I mean it seems amazing,

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:44.600
I mean the, obviously the, the information is

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.920
very powerful. The, the, the genetic tracing.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:49.620
I'm curious to know from your perspective, do

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:55.380
you ever, what percentage of people do you think sign up for these 23 and

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:59.430
me services, and don't quite know that they're

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:02.910
getting themselves into a paternity test of sorts.

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:05.740
is that common, or, or uncommon?

00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:08.090
&gt;&gt; I think most people don't realize the

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.850
power of these types of tests. there's different

00:08:11.850 --> 00:08:13.680
reasons that people test. As you know, they

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.566
might be testing for health reasons, if it's

00:08:15.566 --> 00:08:19.720
23 and Me, whereas they might not realize

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:23.230
the genealogical implications. And it's not always that

00:08:23.230 --> 00:08:25.890
a match finds their birth parent there, with

00:08:25.890 --> 00:08:29.120
an adoptee, for instance. Or a donor-conceived individual.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:31.680
We may find a more distant relative that they're

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:35.380
related to, and still be able to triangulate this

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:39.530
adoptees matches, and identify the probable birth parents. So,

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:42.659
you could be identified, even if you don't test.

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.020
And I think that is just something that our

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:47.630
society is going to have to get used to.

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:50.640
it's just the way things are going and I

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:55.280
believe very strongly in truth. I'm not a scientist by,

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:58.110
training, but science is about truth, and

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:00.470
I don't think that, it's something that

00:09:00.470 --> 00:09:01.960
we should deny. It's something that we

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:04.950
should definitely be moving towards and knowledge

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:10.190
is power so, hopefully, everyone will agree with me and get tested and not be

00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:14.960
upset if they get contacted by a family member that they didn't know about.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.790
&gt;&gt; Exactly. We are definitely in the new

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:20.390
information age. where all of this can really change

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:23.640
our outlooks and our family structures in lots of different ways.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:26.360
What you know, for those of us. I, I, I sort

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.150
of just realized, for those of us who don't know very

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:33.080
much about genealogy at all, how, how far out do you go

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:36.420
in a family structure as a genetic genealogist? Are you interested

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:40.000
in, you know, up to grandparents and maybe second cousins, or

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.530
do, do, do you build out farther than that? Do you

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:45.550
connect whole families? Kind of just give us some idea of how

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:46.430
far out you go?

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:49.000
&gt;&gt; Well, we're interested in our family trees as

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.790
far back as we can go, so with Y

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:55.570
DNA testing which has been used in genetic genealogy

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:58.120
much longer than autosomal DNA tests like 23 and

00:09:58.120 --> 00:10:01.430
me. We're looking way back. We could be looking

00:10:01.430 --> 00:10:03.850
back into the 1400's even, because as you know

00:10:03.850 --> 00:10:08.440
the Y chromosome changes very slowly. Therefore a father

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:11.480
and son will probably have an identical Y chromosome.

00:10:11.480 --> 00:10:13.520
And maybe a grandparent and a great grandparent, a

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:16.880
second great grandfather on that direct paternal line. So

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:19.490
we've used this surname studies to go many, many

00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:23.550
generations back. centuries back. With autosomal DNA, we're not

00:10:23.550 --> 00:10:26.990
looking quite so far back because of the recombination.

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:30.750
However, when we first started using autosomal DNA for

00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:33.970
genetic geneaology, we were told that it was only

00:10:33.970 --> 00:10:38.060
going to work maybe five generations, six generations back.

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:40.980
And especially with our adoption DNA research

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:43.650
we have proven that it works much further

00:10:43.650 --> 00:10:47.340
back. We're able to identify ancestral couples,

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:51.600
a couple centuries ago actually in these, trees

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:57.050
and the way we do that is for instance if an adoptee knows nothing about

00:10:57.050 --> 00:10:59.850
their biological heritage. We would take all

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:03.290
of their family trees of their DNA matches,

00:11:03.290 --> 00:11:05.440
so everyone who's willing to share at 23 and

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:08.470
Me, or Family Tree DNA, or Ancestry DNA. And we

00:11:08.470 --> 00:11:13.140
would start comparing those trees, looking for commonalities and intersections

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:16.240
among their matches' trees, since they don't know anything about

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:18.320
their family tree. And if we see a certain

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:21.990
ancestral couple over and over and over and over, we

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:24.660
can be pretty sure that that's probably one of their

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:28.390
ancestors as well, and if not their ancestor, certainly in

00:11:28.390 --> 00:11:31.270
an ancestral line. One of their branches of

00:11:31.270 --> 00:11:35.100
their family tree would have that ancestral line in

00:11:35.100 --> 00:11:39.050
it. And we've used couples very far back, like,

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:43.050
late 1600s, 1700s, and been able to build down

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:45.200
to the present time. That takes a lot of

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:47.950
work, believe me. And we wouldn't just do it

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:50.170
with one couple, we would do it with various

00:11:50.170 --> 00:11:54.200
couples, build their descendants down to the present, and

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.100
try to see where there's intersections between the

00:11:57.100 --> 00:12:00.290
descendants from those ancestral couples. And if we can

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:03.590
do that, which we sometimes can, we can

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:07.770
sometimes solve this adoption search cases without a close

00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:10.560
relative match. If we get second cousin or

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:14.490
closer, we can almost always solve it. if we're

00:12:14.490 --> 00:12:16.930
only working with third cousins, fourth cousins, fifth

00:12:16.930 --> 00:12:19.290
cousins and more distant, it takes a lot more

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:20.610
work, but it has been done.

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:24.630
&gt;&gt; That's really amazing. you know, we have,

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:28.230
an individual in our course named Sterling, who

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:31.196
is actually submitted his DNA sample to 23

00:12:31.196 --> 00:12:33.750
and Me and gotten results back. And he

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:39.190
has been able to find a, as close a match as a second cousin on the relative

00:12:39.190 --> 00:12:44.150
finder. Now, if you were chatting with him and he was looking for a next step,

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:48.400
what advice would you give to him to sort of deal with trying to reach out

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:50.670
to that person or possibly, you know, finding

00:12:50.670 --> 00:12:53.310
other connections that he could get more information from.

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:56.660
&gt;&gt; There's a couple different things he should do. First of all, he

00:12:56.660 --> 00:13:01.010
may want to join one of our adoption DNA mailing lists. We have

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:03.680
extremely helpful search angels on those

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:06.380
lists who started out as traditional adoption

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:09.230
search angels. So they know how to work with the records. And if

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:13.100
he has any non-identifying information, that can really help to

00:13:13.100 --> 00:13:16.540
use that in conjunction with his DNA results. So we can

00:13:16.540 --> 00:13:18.850
help to teach him on those lists what he needs

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:22.270
to do next. And sometimes, you know, do more than just

00:13:22.270 --> 00:13:24.790
teach him, but hand-hold. And if he gets real close

00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:27.400
to the answer, one of the search angels will jump in

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:29.820
and help. And when I say real close, a second

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:34.390
cousin is really close. So he probably could find someone who'd

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:38.370
be willing to help him work through this matches and

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:40.970
try to identify his birth parents. And the way we would

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:44.700
do that is, we would take that second cousin match

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:48.050
you happen to know what the percentage is that's in common?

00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:53.810
&gt;&gt; I believe it's, it's around, I think its above 1% ish?

00:13:53.810 --> 00:13:56.740
&gt;&gt; Okay, so, we would look at the percent, and

00:13:56.740 --> 00:13:59.490
try to determine if it's a solid second cousin match, or

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:01.560
if it might be a second cousin once removed,

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:04.370
or third cousin. So if his match is around 1%,

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:06.960
that could be a second cousin, it could be

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:09.770
a second cousin once removed. Could be a third cousin.

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:13.020
Could be a first cousin twice removed. depending on

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:14.910
the different ages. So we would look at all of

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:19.360
those possibilities, and we would want that matches family

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:24.990
tree back to great grandparents or preferably great, great grandparents.

00:14:24.990 --> 00:14:27.420
Because they may if they are true seconds cousins they

00:14:27.420 --> 00:14:31.480
will share great grandparents, but if they're second cousins once removed

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:35.710
it might be his great, great-grandparent, and their great-grandparent, or the

00:14:35.710 --> 00:14:38.230
other way around. Or if there's a bunch a removals, it

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:40.480
could even be a little further back in the tree.

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:43.130
So as much as we can get of that family tree,

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:47.080
built from traditional genealogy, we want. If his match doesn't have

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:50.020
it, then we would build that for them. So then we

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:53.690
would look at all of those great-grandparents first. And we would

00:14:53.690 --> 00:14:58.410
build, towards the present with their descendants. And we would try

00:14:58.410 --> 00:15:01.910
to find somebody in the right place at the right time

00:15:01.910 --> 00:15:04.920
who could be this adoptee's birth parent. So we don't know if

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:07.010
it's going to be the mother or the father. So we'd have

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:09.690
to look at both in this case. If it's an adoptee who

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:12.720
already knows their birth mother, which happens quite a bit, now

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:15.310
we know we're just looking for a male in the right place

00:15:15.310 --> 00:15:18.790
at the right time, of the right age, to

00:15:18.790 --> 00:15:21.420
be their birth parent. And if we don't find

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:24.600
anyone from those great grand parents descendants, we have

00:15:24.600 --> 00:15:27.560
to go back one generation. And go to great, great

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:31.920
grandparents and try building them, to the present. And

00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:33.920
if we still have trouble, what I would do

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:37.030
is start looking at his other matches. Preferably his

00:15:37.030 --> 00:15:41.120
next closest matches, but all of his matches are important.

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:43.380
And, we build spreadsheets. So, this is a little

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:46.100
complicated. But, this is what we do. We get

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:49.500
all of the matching segment data into a spreadsheet

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:53.300
and we sort it. So it's in order. Chromosome one,

00:15:53.300 --> 00:15:55.885
start with the beginning of the chromosome to the

00:15:55.885 --> 00:16:00.240
end of the chromosome, so, one base pair all

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:03.850
the way out to the very end, 230,000, whatever

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:06.330
it is. And we go to the next one, and

00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:08.990
chromosome two, three, four, five, and then we start

00:16:08.990 --> 00:16:13.340
looking at people who are overlapping. On these matching segments.

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:16.310
And we try to find groups of people who all

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:18.950
would match each other. Now we since we know that

00:16:18.950 --> 00:16:22.080
there's two chromosomes in each spot, right, it might look

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:25.160
like they're matching, but they're not So we have to

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:28.990
then triangulate, meaning do in common with, if it's Family

00:16:28.990 --> 00:16:31.420
Tree DNA, they have a feature where you can compare

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:34.980
the matches and see if they match, or 23andMe, it's

00:16:34.980 --> 00:16:37.750
even better because we can actually compare them to see if

00:16:37.750 --> 00:16:40.530
they match on the same spot. So if I'm sharing

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:43.870
with someone and sharing with someone else, I can compare them.

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:47.140
So, then we break those groups up into a paternal

00:16:47.140 --> 00:16:50.800
and maternal chromosome. And we don't usually know which is paternal

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:53.410
which is maternal, so we just call them A and B.

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:56.520
So, we will have chromosome one A and chromosome one B.

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.868
And we'll have groups of overlapping matches. Now

00:16:59.868 --> 00:17:01.120
what would we would do is try to

00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:05.220
get the family tree information, the regular genealogy

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:09.260
that, of, from documentary research. And compare these family

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:12.339
trees, of the matches since the adoptee doesn't

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:15.359
have one, and we look for commonalities and

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:18.240
overlaps. So if we can find an ancestral

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:22.200
couple that appears in some of these overlapping matches

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:24.500
then we know that that also has to be in

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:28.339
the adoptee's family tree, and why is that? That's because

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:30.710
each piece of DNA can only come from one of

00:17:30.710 --> 00:17:34.160
our ancestors right? Now its probably an ancestral couple, so

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:36.220
we won't know if it's from the man or the

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:40.410
woman of the couple, but that's okay, because we know

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:43.550
that this couple then, goes in their family tree. And

00:17:43.550 --> 00:17:47.360
in this way, we can give adoptees their family tree back

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:50.470
piece by piece. So even if we can't automatically

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:53.300
tell them who their birth parents are, we can start

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:56.550
giving them pieces of their heritage back. Which is incredibly

00:17:56.550 --> 00:17:59.970
meaningful for adoptees I found. I think it's hard for

00:17:59.970 --> 00:18:02.640
those of us who aren't adopted to understand that,

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:04.870
but I've had a lot of adoptees say to me,

00:18:04.870 --> 00:18:08.240
I have ancestors. Like it's so strange for them to

00:18:08.240 --> 00:18:12.390
