more and more, and more. because Ann Wojciciki from 23andme

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:50.760
has this slide she shows in her presentations where she

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:54.160
say's what we knew a couple of years ago. And it's

00:27:54.160 --> 00:27:58.140
just like a few dots here and there across the genome and what we know now,

00:27:58.140 --> 00:28:01.250
like what's been identified. To be significant. And

00:28:01.250 --> 00:28:03.720
it's just full of them now. So all though

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:09.040
that that's not my area of expertise. I know that this is meaningful and is just

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:10.460
going to get more and more so. So

00:28:10.460 --> 00:28:12.910
hearing that from you just confirms what I thought.

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:16.000
&gt;&gt; Great, I'm glad to hear that. Well you

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.970
know? We're really intriged that you say, you know,

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:21.560
genetics is a passion of yours but it wasn't actually

00:28:21.560 --> 00:28:24.430
what you studied. Can you tell us a bit more about

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:26.560
what you did before you got into this and sort

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:30.790
of what your segue was. Were you just a super, super

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:34.190
nerd spend all your free time in genetics. Or was

00:28:34.190 --> 00:28:37.850
this just a, a really fun hobby for you. Genetics was

00:28:37.850 --> 00:28:40.050
always something that I was interested in, but I had

00:28:40.050 --> 00:28:44.250
not studied it. In fact, I was a music and theater

00:28:44.250 --> 00:28:47.190
major in college, and I had fallen in love with genetics

00:28:47.190 --> 00:28:49.550
just prior to that in my senior year in high school

00:28:49.550 --> 00:28:53.640
when I was in AP bio. We had a little genetics,

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:57.710
section as part of our course work. And I absolutely loved

00:28:57.710 --> 00:29:00.340
it. So I should have taken the clue then. And I,

00:29:00.340 --> 00:29:02.490
I loved it enough that I did think about changing my

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:05.040
major. And I even investigated it. But I already had a

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:09.550
scholarship for music at USC, and they didn't have a genetics,

00:29:09.550 --> 00:29:11.730
undergraduate program or I very well may have done

00:29:11.730 --> 00:29:14.370
it. But I just stuck with my original plan

00:29:14.370 --> 00:29:17.380
and many years later, here I end up back

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:21.960
again loving genetics, but this time it took over my

00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:25.020
life. So I had started as a genealogist in

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:28.630
2002, I think was when I really got involved,

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:31.180
and I was looking at making a family tree

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:34.720
for my niece's wedding. And I, the type of person

00:29:34.720 --> 00:29:37.060
who jumps in with both feet. And I did

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:41.450
that and, got kind of obsessed. did genealogy for a few

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:44.490
years before I got really interested in the genetics

00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:48.890
part of it. we, we're just using Y-DNA and mtDNA

00:29:48.890 --> 00:29:50.870
at the time, which I still thought was interesting.

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:53.890
But I wasn't quite as fascinated as I am with

00:29:53.890 --> 00:29:57.370
autosomal DNA. And that's really become my focus although

00:29:57.370 --> 00:30:00.590
I use the other types in conjunction with it many

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:04.390
times especially in adoption searches. So how did

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:05.930
I get into it? So I started writing the

00:30:05.930 --> 00:30:09.520
blog. And I got so many questions from

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:12.820
people, and so much interest, that it literally started

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:19.550
taking over my life. I had tons of comments on the blog, I had tons of private

00:30:19.550 --> 00:30:23.090
emails of people wanting help, particularly people who

00:30:23.090 --> 00:30:26.610
were searching for close family members like adoptees, and

00:30:26.610 --> 00:30:30.630
people who had discovered close family members, and hadn't expected

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:33.540
it. there's so many people out there that this is

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:37.770
happening to, you'd be surprised. And I sometimes wonder if

00:30:37.770 --> 00:30:41.540
there's much more of that in our society than we realize,

00:30:41.540 --> 00:30:43.560
but then I think that it's also possible that the

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:46.410
people who are drawn to testing, are the people who maybe

00:30:46.410 --> 00:30:49.110
felt a little different, or felt like something was missing

00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:51.640
in their lives. So it's hard to say which it is.

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:53.930
But anyway, the result was, that I was

00:30:53.930 --> 00:30:58.260
completely overwhelmed. So I had been an actress,

00:30:58.260 --> 00:31:00.000
for many years, and then when I had

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:03.180
my son, I had transitioned behind the camera, and

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:06.410
was producing commercials. And my poor partner has

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:10.440
had to completely take over our production business because

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:16.850
I work about 18 hours a day, 7 days a week doing genetic genealogy. And I never

00:31:16.850 --> 00:31:19.300
would have imagined it would have become my career. I

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:23.200
don't have a science background, I've certainly taken science classes

00:31:23.200 --> 00:31:25.510
and always loved them, but that wasn't the direction I

00:31:25.510 --> 00:31:30.010
took with my career. So to go from entertainment and

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:32.818
to end up in a science career in my forties

00:31:32.818 --> 00:31:35.970
is definitely not something I would have ever imagined. But

00:31:35.970 --> 00:31:38.970
it is so fascinating. Everyday, I wake up in the

00:31:38.970 --> 00:31:42.230
morning and I immediately want to jump out of bed and

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:44.230
run down to my computer and see what

00:31:44.230 --> 00:31:48.340
new fascinating things had tra, have transpired overnight and,

00:31:48.340 --> 00:31:51.640
believe me, there is always something. I'm very

00:31:51.640 --> 00:31:55.540
involved with all of the genetic genealogy mailing lists.

00:31:55.540 --> 00:31:57.160
So I spend a lot of time answering

00:31:57.160 --> 00:32:01.360
questions on those. And I do help adoptees for

00:32:01.360 --> 00:32:03.650
free. So a lot of my time is spent

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:07.420
as a volunteer. I do some consulting. But probably

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:09.830
the most amazing thing that's come from it

00:32:09.830 --> 00:32:13.930
is, I am now the Genetic Genealogy Consultant

00:32:13.930 --> 00:32:16.165
on Finding Your Roots with Henry Louis Gates

00:32:16.165 --> 00:32:19.990
Jr. and also Genealogy Roadshow. And there's also

00:32:19.990 --> 00:32:24.310
another Fox pilot, which I don't know if anything will come of it. So, there are

00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:27.530
currently three television shows that I am doing

00:32:27.530 --> 00:32:33.240
consulting for. And, so now, my entertainment background, and

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:36.600
this new career, that I never planned on, have

00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:39.120
kind of come together in a way I would never

00:32:39.120 --> 00:32:43.250
have imagined. So it's been quite a ride. I mean,

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:46.240
amazing. They say sometimes you just fall into something. And

00:32:46.240 --> 00:32:48.780
I wish I'd fallen into it in my twenties, but

00:32:48.780 --> 00:32:51.360
still great that I eventually got where I am now.

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:55.650
what do you think about the current state of genetic

00:32:55.650 --> 00:32:58.360
genealogists in the country, or in the world? Do you

00:32:58.360 --> 00:33:00.960
think that we're in need of, of more people who can

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:03.330
serve the same kind of role you and your blog serve?

00:33:03.330 --> 00:33:06.460
&gt;&gt; Yeah. That's a terrific question, Matt, and

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:08.644
it is something that I think about every

00:33:08.644 --> 00:33:13.170
day. Because I have so many people coming to me for help, I can't possibly help

00:33:13.170 --> 00:33:17.750
them all. I stay up all hours of the night and I, you know, don't do

00:33:17.750 --> 00:33:20.290
a lot of, social activities so I can

00:33:20.290 --> 00:33:23.540
help these people. It's really fulfilling. And I prioritize

00:33:23.540 --> 00:33:27.760
the ones who have a really emotionally important question.

00:33:27.760 --> 00:33:30.840
Like they have discovered something of great significance to

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:34.810
their, close family. And I just can't keep up

00:33:34.810 --> 00:33:37.570
with it. And I need people that are doing what

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:39.440
I'm doing that I can send these people to.

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:42.200
And I have a couple colleagues that I am able

00:33:42.200 --> 00:33:45.160
to refer people to and there's a great network

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:48.890
of search angels who have learned to do genetic genealogy.

00:33:48.890 --> 00:33:51.540
Who are also helping adoptees and those like

00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:55.220
them who have an unknown parentage, usually unknown father,

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:58.510
sometimes donor-conceived individuals. But it's even more than

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:01.280
just that. I have a lot of, just you

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:04.970
know, people interested in their ancestry and in

00:34:04.970 --> 00:34:09.139
their genealogy. Who are either are genealogists or aren't

00:34:09.139 --> 00:34:10.980
and are just interested in learning more, because

00:34:10.980 --> 00:34:14.489
they've heard about DNA testing. There's such a huge

00:34:14.489 --> 00:34:18.020
demand for this. And maybe a year ago, some

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:19.820
people had come to me and asked me you

00:34:19.820 --> 00:34:21.449
know, if they wanted to have a career in

00:34:21.449 --> 00:34:26.710
Genetic Genealogy, was there was there a demand for it?

00:34:26.710 --> 00:34:29.719
And it's changed. Really then, maybe a year ago,

00:34:29.719 --> 00:34:31.949
two years ago, there wasn't much of a demand

00:34:31.949 --> 00:34:34.850
for it. And in the last year or two,

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:39.860
it has literally exploded. So now I absolutely would say

00:34:39.860 --> 00:34:44.400
that there is room for genetic genealogy consultants. People who

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:48.110
are willing to learn what we're doing. And if they

00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:50.920
have a background in genealogy that would be great. And

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:53.679
if they don't that's fine too. They'll have to learn both

00:34:53.679 --> 00:34:55.989
sides of it. So they'll have to learn the DNA

00:34:55.989 --> 00:34:59.120
part and the genealogy part. But if they're adventurous and

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:01.870
they're looking for a new career and they love detective

00:35:01.870 --> 00:35:05.370
work because that's exactly what this is. Then I would strongly

00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:07.380
recommend that they look into this as a career.

00:35:07.380 --> 00:35:11.720
&gt;&gt; Well, great. Sort of as our parting words here in, in the

00:35:11.720 --> 00:35:15.100
same vein is there any other specific advice or resources you would give to

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:17.700
someone who's particularly moved by this

00:35:17.700 --> 00:35:19.450
subject and wants to investigate about the

00:35:19.450 --> 00:35:23.332
possibility of studying more? Are there some places they can go to? Sort of

00:35:23.332 --> 00:35:24.340
[COUGH]

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:27.250
learn more about how to become a genetic genealogist that you recommend?

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:30.290
&gt;&gt; Yes. Because the field is so fast

00:35:30.290 --> 00:35:33.160
moving there are very few books that really address

00:35:33.160 --> 00:35:36.100
the subject. And every day we have someone asking,

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:38.690
you know, is there are genetic genealogy for dummies

00:35:38.690 --> 00:35:41.180
book. And there isn't. Not yet at least.

00:35:41.180 --> 00:35:43.270
And that's because those of us who've tried to

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:46.090
write them find that they are so quickly outdated.

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:49.670
That trying to get something published is very difficult,

00:35:49.670 --> 00:35:52.290
that's up to date. So we always recommend that

00:35:52.290 --> 00:35:55.710
you read the blogs. You read my blog, Blaine's

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:59.110
blog, Rebre-, Roberta Estes blog. There's some other really

00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:01.720
good ones out there. Kitty Cooper has recently started

00:36:01.720 --> 00:36:06.550
writing some fantastic resources. And most of all, join

00:36:06.550 --> 00:36:09.330
our mailing list, because that's where you really get

00:36:09.330 --> 00:36:11.910
help from the experts. And the people who've been

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:14.730
doing this from the very beginning are very generous

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:17.080
with their time, and they're on those lists. So

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:21.120
join the International Society of Genetic Genealogy. It's free.

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:26.120
It's ISOGG, isogg.org. And then you'll get an invitation

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:29.180
to join the DNA newbie list which I happen

00:36:29.180 --> 00:36:32.100
to administer, and you can go there and ask

00:36:32.100 --> 00:36:35.620
the most basic questions. and we have people who've

00:36:35.620 --> 00:36:37.030
been on the list for quite a while, so

00:36:37.030 --> 00:36:39.910
we also have more intermediate discussions and sometimes even

00:36:39.910 --> 00:36:44.150
venture into more advanced. So, just keep reading everything you can.

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:47.120
That's how I learned this. I got on the list and

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:50.540
I made myself read every single message, whether it made sense

00:36:50.540 --> 00:36:53.530
to me or not, and it didn't at first. But I think

00:36:53.530 --> 00:36:56.250
it works like you know, osmosis for a lack of a

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:59.180
better word. It starts to seep in after a while and

00:36:59.180 --> 00:37:01.920
it starts to make sense, and you don't even know how

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:05.620
that happened because it, you didn't even know what you were reading.

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:08.720
But our brains work, you know, mysterious ways.

00:37:08.720 --> 00:37:10.860
And, I, I promise you, if you get on

00:37:10.860 --> 00:37:13.370
the list and you read everything that everyone's writing,

00:37:13.370 --> 00:37:16.420
especially people like Ann Turner, who was one of

00:37:16.420 --> 00:37:19.840
the first pioneer genetic genealogists, and she wrote the

00:37:19.840 --> 00:37:24.630
book Tracing Your Roots with DNA. And she's on

00:37:24.630 --> 00:37:27.350
those lists. I mean, you can't access a better

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:30.860
resource than her, and a lot of my other

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:33.580
colleagues, Tim Jansen is amazing, he's on those

00:37:33.580 --> 00:37:37.270
lists. So join us, and we'll help you learn.

00:37:37.270 --> 00:37:41.540
&gt;&gt; Great. CC, it's been a pleasure chatting with you. I hope

00:37:41.540 --> 00:37:45.169
you'll join us again maybe in the discussion forums for our course.

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:47.660
&gt;&gt; That'll be great. I'd love to.

